    "question": "What is the main advantage of using a binary tree over a linear data structure?",
    "options": ["A. Binary trees allow for faster insertion and deletion", "B. Binary trees are easier to implement", "C. Binary trees always guarantee logarithmic time complexity", "D. Binary trees do not require any additional memory overhead"],
    "correctIndex": 0,
    "explanation": "Binary trees can provide faster insertion and deletion operations compared to linear data structures like arrays or linked lists, especially when the tree is balanced. However, it's important to note that binary trees do not always guarantee logarithmic time complexity (option C is incorrect), as the performance depends on the tree being balanced. Binary trees are not necessarily easier to implement (option B is incorrect) and they do require additional memory for pointers (option D is incorrect)."
