    "question": "Which of the following is a key characteristic of the Harvard architecture in computer organization?",
    "options": ["A. It uses a single bus for both data and instructions", "B. It has separate memory spaces for data and instructions", "C. It relies on a unified cache for data and instructions", "D. It is primarily used in general-purpose computing systems"],
    "correctIndex": 1,
    "explanation": "The Harvard architecture is characterized by having separate memory spaces for data and instructions. This allows for simultaneous access to both data and instructions, which can improve performance in certain applications. In contrast, the Von Neumann architecture uses a single bus for both data and instructions (option A). Harvard architecture does not necessarily rely on a unified cache (option C) and it is often used in embedded systems and digital signal processing, not just general-purpose computing (option D)."
  },
